Here’s a focused stack: tools you’ll likely need to run Tap919 (Middleman + StreetCode + BlackMind + AetherDesk + Runner affiliate system), what they do, and whether you can realistically replace them with your own builds.

***

## Core Cloud & Runtime

- Cloud provider (primary compute)
  - Examples: AWS, GCP, Azure, Fly.io.
  - Function: Run Middleman (FastAPI), databases, background workers, dashboards.
  - Replaceable?: In theory with your own bare‑metal or colocation, but not worth it in the 120‑day window; use managed cloud.

- Edge platform
  - Example: Cloudflare Workers. [screenshotone](https://screenshotone.com/blog/cloudflare-workers/)
  - Function: Edge gateway in front of Middleman (auth, routing, rate limits, affiliate link handling, low‑latency API façade).
  - Replaceable?: You could build an Nginx/Lua or Envoy‑based edge in front of your core, but Cloudflare gives global PoPs, DNS, and WAF instantly; keep it.

- Container runtime / orchestration
  - Examples: Docker, Docker Compose, maybe a light Kubernetes (or ECS/Fargate).
  - Function: Package and deploy Middleman, background workers, possibly BlackMind services.
  - Replaceable?: You *could* script everything with raw VMs, but containers are standard; don’t rebuild.

***

## Data & Storage

- Primary database
  - Examples: Postgres via Supabase, Neon, RDS, or similar.
  - Function: Store Tenants, API keys, PricingRules, UsageEvents, Affiliates, Payouts.
  - Replaceable?: You could build on SQLite only, but Postgres is the right long‑term call; building your own DB is a hard no.

- Analytics / warehouse (optional but strong)
  - Examples: BigQuery, Snowflake, or Postgres + DuckDB for analytics.
  - Function: Deeper usage analysis, cost modeling, cohort tracking.
  - Replaceable?: You can roll simple analytics as SQL over Postgres; full warehouse not required day 0.

- Object storage
  - Examples: S3, Cloudflare R2, Backblaze B2.
  - Function: Store logs, exports, runner kits, static marketing/media assets.
  - Replaceable?: You could serve from GitHub + CDN, but proper object storage is cheap and robust.

***

## Billing, Payments & Accounting

- Payment processor
  - Example: Stripe.
  - Function: Take card payments, manage customers, invoices, payouts, disputes.
  - Replaceable?: You *could* integrate directly with networks or use crypto, but Stripe is de facto; do not rebuild payments.

- Billing/usage system
  - Using Stripe Billing for usage‑based pricing. [stripe](https://stripe.com/resources/more/usage-based-pricing-strategy-for-saas)
  - Function: Metered billing, recurring invoices, trials, proration.
  - Replaceable?: You’re partially replacing “usage logic” with Middleman, but Stripe still handles invoicing and financial compliance; you shouldn’t rebuild invoices and tax logic.

- Accounting / books
  - Examples: QuickBooks, Xero.
  - Function: Track expenses, revenue, taxes, financial reports.
  - Replaceable?: Self‑built is a tax nightmare; integrate your Stripe/PayPal exports and usage data instead.

***

## Observability & Monitoring

- Logs and metrics
  - Examples: Grafana Cloud, Datadog, Logtail, or ELK stack.
  - Function: System logs, performance metrics, alerts.
  - Replaceable?: You can roll a basic ELK or Loki/Grafana stack yourself; but a managed service saves time early.

- Tracing / OTEL backend
  - Examples: Tempo (Grafana stack), Honeycomb, Lightstep, Jaeger.
  - Function: Collect OpenTelemetry traces from Middleman and related services for debugging and cost/latency insights. [blog.cloudflare](https://blog.cloudflare.com/api-gateway/)
  - Replaceable?: You can self‑host Jaeger/Tempo; this is one area where building your own *collector* could be done, but using existing open‑source OTEL backends is smarter than starting from scratch.

- Uptime/health monitoring
  - Examples: Better Uptime, Healthchecks.io, Pingdom.
  - Function: External pings to /internal/ping, /v1/agent/ping; alert on downtime.
  - Replaceable?: You can script your own monitors and send alerts via webhooks, but a SaaS monitor is faster early.

***

## Dev, Code, CI/CD

- Code hosting
  - Example: GitHub (you’re already on it).
  - Function: Repo hosting, PRs, issues, releases.
  - Replaceable?: Self‑host Git (Gitea, GitLab) is possible but not worth the overhead right now.

- CI/CD pipeline
  - Examples: GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, CircleCI.
  - Function: Test, build Docker images, deploy to cloud/Workers.
  - Replaceable?: You *could* build your own deploy tooling in StreetCode or a custom orchestrator, but CI SaaS is very cheap and aligns with standard workflows.

- Secrets management
  - Examples: Doppler, 1Password for Business, AWS Secrets Manager.
  - Function: Store API keys, DB strings, Stripe secrets, provider keys.
  - Replaceable?: You can store secrets in `.env` and keep them out of git, but a secrets manager is safer; building your own secure vault is non‑trivial.

***

## Product & Front‑Of‑House

- Marketing site / CMS
  - Examples: Next.js + Vercel, Webflow, or a static site via Cloudflare Pages.
  - Function: Tap919 marketing page, pricing, docs, affiliate pitch, content flywheel hub.
  - Replaceable?: You *are* going to build some of this (it fits your “edge storefront” story), but leveraging a framework like Next.js is a good baseline.

- Documentation platform
  - Examples: GitBook, ReadMe, Docusaurus.
  - Function: API docs, agent capability docs, Runner guides.
  - Replaceable?: You can build your own docs system inside StreetCode/AetherDesk, but early adoption and SEO are easier with something like Docusaurus or GitBook.

- Support & ticketing
  - Examples: Zendesk, Help Scout, Intercom.
  - Function: Inbox, support tickets, help center, chat widget.
  - Replaceable?: You can roll your own minimal “AetherDesk support” module later; in the first 120 days, using email + a lightweight tool is fine.

***

## Comms & Collaboration

- Internal chat
  - Example: Slack, Discord.
  - Function: Internal comms, incident channels, dev chat.
  - Replaceable?: You could embed chat inside AetherDesk, but external Slack/Discord is standard and fast.

- Project/issue tracking
  - Examples: Linear, Jira, GitHub Projects.
  - Function: Track 120‑day roadmap, war plan execution, bug tracking.
  - Replaceable?: You can embed “Nexus board” functionality in AetherDesk or StreetCode; for the sprint, GitHub Issues/Projects is enough.

***

## AI & Model Providers

- LLM providers
  - Examples: OpenAI, Anthropic, Mistral, Google, etc.
  - Function: Base models behind some `tap919:` lanes.
  - Replaceable?: Long‑term you can run open‑source models via your own infra; short‑term you don’t want to self‑host everything.

- Vector / search infra (optional)
  - Examples: pgvector, Qdrant, Weaviate.
  - Function: RAG/sampling layer for docs, usage history, agent knowledge.
  - Replaceable?: You can build simple RAG via Postgres + pgvector; no need to rely on a third‑party SaaS vector DB unless you want managed scaling.

***

## Affiliate & Runner System

- Affiliate management / payouts (optional external)
  - Examples: Rewardful, Tolt. [rewardful](https://www.rewardful.com)
  - Function: Track referrals, calculate commissions, manage payouts for SaaS affiliates.
  - Replaceable?: This is exactly what you’re partially building:
    - Affiliate table.
    - Runner dashboards.
    - Commission calculations.
    - Payout previews.
    - You can replace a Rewardful/Tolt‑style stack with your own capabilities plus Stripe/PayPal payouts.

- Payout rails
  - Examples: Stripe Connect, PayPal Payouts, Wise Business.
  - Function: Actually send money to Runners.
  - Replaceable?: You don’t want to build your own bank/payout system; you just orchestrate on top.

***

## Analytics & Growth

- Product analytics
  - Examples: PostHog, Amplitude, Mixpanel.
  - Function: Understand user behavior in StreetCode/AetherDesk, funnel drop‑off, feature usage.
  - Replaceable?: You can instrument much of this yourself with events stored in your DB and visualized in your own dashboards; a SaaS tool is faster, your own is more on‑brand long‑term.

- Web analytics
  - Examples: Plausible, Google Analytics.
  - Function: Marketing site performance, conversion tracking to signup.
  - Replaceable?: You can log basic web analytics to your own DB or server logs; using a simple privacy‑friendly analytics tool is fine initially.

- Email/marketing automation
  - Examples: ConvertKit, MailerLite, Customer.io.
  - Function: Drip sequences for Runners, agency leads, free→paid conversion.
  - Replaceable?: AetherDesk could eventually become your engagement engine; early on, a lightweight email platform is better than nothing.

***

## Legal, Compliance & Admin (Minimal)

- E‑signature & contract management
  - Examples: DocuSign, HelloSign.
  - Function: Agency agreements, enterprise deals, affiliate terms.
  - Replaceable?: You can do basic click‑wrap in your app, but e‑signature tools are standard for larger deals.

- Policy templates / compliance
  - Tools: Templates from legal SaaS or internal documents.
  - Function: Terms of service, privacy policy, DPA, affiliate agreement.
  - Replaceable?: Should be authored by real counsel; not a place to build tooling from scratch in 120 days.

